1) USD/TRY Exchange Rates from 01.2005 to 11.2020

As it can be seen below, the exchange rate of USD/TRY has followed these values, with concerning codes:

setwd("D:/Lectures/(2020-2021) Lectures Junior/IE360/Assignments/1")

library(ggplot2)
library(knitr)
library(markdown)

exc <- read.table(file="hw1_data1.txt", header=TRUE)

attach(exc)

usdplot <- ggplot(exc, aes(date, usd))

usdplot + geom_point(color="red") + geom_line() + 
          labs(title = "USD/TRY at Each Month From 01.2005 to 11.2020", x = "Date (in months)", y = "USD-TRY Exchange Rate",  
               caption = "https://evds2.tcmb.gov.tr/index.php?/evds/archiveMarket/collapse_0/5862/DataGroup/turkish/bie_dkdovizgn/")

# + geom_text(aes(label=months), angle = 90, size = 2, nudge_y = 0.2)
# + theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 90, hjust = 1))

save.image("hw1_data1_R.RData")

ggsave("plot1.png", width = 80, height = 10, limitsize = FALSE)

Its shape is not changing at all at the beginning, 01.2005, and following months. Yet, sometimes USD/TRY value increases a little bit and continues its route with higher values, like step functions. Besides, in the last years its shape is changing so rapidly because of these reasons:

  1. Economical fluctuationsâ freqeuncy and their amplitude due to domestic and foreign policies of the ruling party.
  2. Having a decreasing confidence level against Turkish economics concerning not only for consumers but also producers/investors.

Also, if we compare different halves of each graphs, it can be concluded that shape of the graph is significantly changed. At the first half, we have a stable exchange rate but at the second half of the graph, we have unstable exchange rate that changes a Also, year after year, its graph doesnât change significantly at the first time when the data are taken, but at the end the difference between years is much more.

3) Banksâ Total Amount of Dollars (in millions) from 01.2012 to 08.2020

library(knitr)
library(markdown)

From these graphs, it can be concluded that if each graph is halved and compared, TCMBâs graph shows more linear shape besides its second half, when its shape is again increasing same before but not as ragged as before. Yet, in the second half of the TCMBâs data, it can be observed that there is again increase but its increases make more great fluctuations. Also, if it is analyzed year after year, there is no similarity or stability, its values change every year.

When it comes to examine the Google Trendsâ data, there is no similarity between the first half and the second half of the graph. Also, each year has different search volume amount not related to the former one. At the beginning, its shape is ragged and has deep rags, but at the second half, its increase has more stable shape but again have rags not as deep before. At the end of the graph, its shape has the greatest peaks and pits.
